Context

Most would agree that data science should always start and end with data visualization. It allows the scientist to understand the data, its structure and distribution, but also to connect with the public, by creating easily understandable content to facilitate communication.

In the previous workshops, we have learned how to: - Efficiently visualize data and results - Manipulate Data to facilitate its analysis - Optimize replicability and sharing of our codes

… and all of this makes it hard to leave the R environment! Still, most of us still are leaving the comfort of R whenever we are faced with spatial data, splitting our workflow and creating different codes, different processes and ultimately resulting in a loss of time and efficiency.

R as a GIS and Mapping Software

To address this problem, multiple libraries have been made available in R in order to deal with spatial data, its visualisation, its manipulation and its analysis. the most notable are probably:

ggmap : This package is an extension for ggplot2 allowing the plotting of spatial data into maps rgdal : An interface to access gdal, a spatial data processing library rgeos : An interface to access geos, a spatial vector data processing library maptools : Provides mapping functions tmap : A mapping package leafy : Used to create interactive maps. this is one of the most used package for online maps sp raster spdep

Goals

reading a raster from file loading basemap from internet loading satellite data from internet reading shapefile

saving layers mapping (multiple views, legends, scales, titles, etc.) exporting maps

manipulate shapefile rasterize raster calculator vectorize buffer clip zonal statistics landscape metrics
